  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Lucia Weston hopes that Deborah Weston will come to a meeting on the 25th. She mentions Orange Scott, Ellis Gray Loring, Henry B. Stanton, and Amos Dresser as prospective speakers. Lucia continues writing this letter on Thursday, [January] 26 through Tuesday, [January 31]. Lucia tells about the pledges for money made at a meeting. Lucia is president of the ladies&apos; society and she lists the members of her family who hold office in various abolitionist organizations. She describes Amos Dresser. She went to a meeting called to raise money for the Liberator newspaper. She ends the letter with family news.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">On the first page of the stationary is an engraving by P. Reason, entitled &quot;A Colored Young Man of the City of New York,&quot; 1835. Lucia Weston explains: &quot;Though you are not an oppressor, I write to you on this paper because I had no other in the house.&quot;</subfield>
  </datafield>
